The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | CAB initiative   Cricket awards   Schools golf   Hole-in-one   Billiards
                                                   IN THE CITY                         
	 CAB initiative 
    The Cricket Association of Bengal is planning to organise a few audio-visual sessions for the junior cricketers of the state starting from the second week of August. According to the CAB joint secretary Biswarup Dey, former Bengal cricketers will be invited to hold some classes with the junior players. Initially, the sessions will be held once a week on Saturdays.         
	Meanwhile, a level A refresher course for the East Zone coaches under the guidance of the National Cricket Academy will also be organised by the CAB from 14-16 August at the Eden.               
	 Cricket awards       The Cricket Association of Bengal, on Thursday, named Subhojit Bannerjee the best university cricketer of the year. Sayan Deb Bera of the South 24 Parganas and Sourav Das of Nadia were selected the best district cricketers of the year for the under-16 and under-19 categories respectively.         
	Meanwhile, the amount yet to be recovered from the previous dispensation of the CAB, regarding the expenses of the inaugural edition of the Indian Premier League, was not Rs 1.75 crore but Rs 2,06,57,500, head of the five-member special committee, Usha Nath Banerjee, informed on Thursday.                     
	Schools golf 
    The fifth inter-school golf championship will be held at the Royal Calcutta Golf Club on Saturday and Sunday where 220 juniors from 15 schools will participate. The tournament has been divided into two categories  under-13 and above-13.                     
	 Hole-in-one       Indrajit Bhalotia, playing over the course of the RCGC on July 2, holed out in one stroke at second hole.                     
	Billiards
    Akram Khan thrashed Aamer Hussain 4-0 in the final of the state billiards championship to lift his maiden senior billiards title at the Bengal Rowing Club. In the womens event, Sunita Damani beat Neeta Kothari 2-0 to retain her title. Akram, having made the highest break of the championship, a 101 unfinished in an earlier round, wrapped up the match in no time.                                                                                                                         
